An app is NOT pushed until `verify` passes. That discipline is the product: the repo only ever
contains finished, verified work.

## Log

2026-07-15  Scaffolded. No work started.

2026-07-15  source: done.
            Primary is Schneider WP75 Rev 4, "Comparing UPS System Design Configurations." Free,
            fetched, read in full. Chosen because it is the rare free document that publishes BOTH
            a one line AND its own stated verdict on that one line, which is the only thing that
            makes a verify phase possible here.
            The finding that reshaped the project: Uptime's own public pages never use the words
            N, N+1, or 2N. That vocabulary is industry convention mapped onto their tiers, not
            their definition, and their Tier Standard: Topology is gated and unread. So the tool
            does not output tiers. It cannot honestly. See sources/SOURCES.md.
            Located but deliberately unused this pass: RD111, RD108 (both free, both explicitly
            Tier III labelled, both name RPP and busway as nodes, which WP75 does not), WP48,
            DOE FEMP, OCP. Logged in SOURCES.md so the next pass does not repeat the search.

2026-07-15  learn: done. reference/concurrent-maintainability.md.
            Wrote up the tier caveat, the three way outcome of pulling a component (up / lit but
            unprotected / dark), redundant components against redundant paths, and the cord count
            being where these designs are actually decided.

2026-07-15  build: done. build/index.html + engine.js + topologies.js.
            Zero dependencies, no CDN, no build step. Hand rolled SVG.
            All five WP75 figures traced node by node and edge by edge at high magnification,
            including which lines are solid and which are dashed, since the dashed ones are the
            alternate feeds and reading them backwards inverts the answer. The Figure 5 STS ring
            in particular took real tracing: each UPS feeds two STS, one as primary and one as
            secondary, and it is symmetric.
            Engine models the WP75 p.3 definition properly, including its second clause: a load
            that stays lit only by closing a bypass is on raw utility, and that is a FAIL, not a
            pass. So "fed" and "fed on protected power" are tracked separately.

2026-07-15  verify: done. 31 checks, 0 failures. node verify/verify.js
            Every expectation quotes WP75's own words. No tier assertions, on purpose.
            The verify phase earned its keep three times:
            1. Mutation testing found the unplanned fault analysis was DEAD CODE: breaking its
               logic changed no test result. Cut it rather than ship it. No published claim to
               check it against, and it would have been wrong anyway (a real UPS has an internal
               static bypass, WP75 p.5, which these figures do not draw).
            2. Mutation testing found a REAL BUG: Figure 7's bus tie was encoded one way, so side
               B could never back feed side A. Fixed, and now covered by an assertion tied to the
               p.16 claim about what that tie is for.
            3. A structural check in the browser found two node boxes silently overlapping in the
               Figure 5 layout. Fixed, and promoted to a permanent layout test.
            All six engine mutants now go red. Baseline is green. The suite measures something.

2026-07-15  publish: done. Pushed. Verify gate passed first, per the repo rule.
            `live` stays todo: GitHub Pages is not enabled for this repo yet, so there is no
            hosted demo link. The app runs locally by opening build/index.html. Nothing to
            configure. Flipping `live` needs Pages turned on, which is a repo setting.
